Whitehead‚Äôs book explores the true story of the Dozier School, a reform school in Florida which operated for 111 years. It‚Äôs a devastating look at abuse at a reform school in Jim Crow-era Florida. Ultimately, it‚Äôs a powerful tale of human perseverance, dignity, and redemption. See you next week for our third pick! Tonight is the Night! Let's highlight our 2022 Honorees Again! Gabriela Torres De Medina Boba Luba Tea Gabriela Torres was born in Cuahuila, Mexico and immigrated to the US when she was three. Growing up in the inner city of Atlanta, she always wanted to do better for her children. In 2011, she started a successful real estate business, but in 2018, she was called to sell her real estate business in order to create a safe and healthy environment for local people to work. That vision blossomed into Boba Lubu Tea, the first bubble tea shop to be owned by a Mexican American woman. Boba Lubu is a coffee and tea shop designed to bring together all ages in fellowship and created to share the taste of Gaby's culture to the community. Managing to keep her company running through the pandemic, Gabriela now strives to grow her business, minister to her employees, and inspire others whenever given the opportunity.

May is Asian/Pacific American Heritage Month With her election in 1964, Rep. Patsy Mink became the first woman of color and the first Asian American woman to serve in the U.S. Congress. She represented the people of Hawaii during two periods, the first from 1965 to 1977 and again from 1990 until her death in 2002. Mink was a vigorous and tireless champion for girls and women, an early and vocal opponent to the Vietnam War, and a leader on issues involving education, the environment, welfare, and civil rights. She is perhaps best known for her work shepherding and defending Title IX, the legislation that passed almost 50 years ago on June 23, 1972, that changed the face of education by prohibiting sex-discrimination in federally funded educational programs.

May is Asian/Pacific American Heritage Month ‚Äì a celebration of Asians and Pacific Islanders in the United States. A rather broad term, Asian/Pacific encompasses all of the Asian continent and the Pacific islands of Melanesia (New Guinea, New Caledonia, Vanuatu, Fiji and the Solomon Islands), Micronesia (Marianas, Guam, Wake Island, Palau, Marshall Islands, Kiribati, Nauru and the Federated States of Micronesia) and Polynesia (New Zealand, Hawaiian Islands, Rotuma, Midway Islands, Samoa, American Samoa, Tonga, Tuvalu, Cook Islands, French Polynesia and Easter Island).

#TalentTuesday Doers, do you value your gift? People will treat your gift how you treat your gift. If you value your gift on the level, it should be valued, so will others. The best way to value your gift is by using your talents to benefit others; in turn, you will reap the rewards as a result of using that talent. Since God has entrusted us with specific resources, gifts, and abilities, it is our responsibility to be faithful stewards of our God-given gifts. We will be participating in the ‚ÄúRedefining Black‚Äù campaign presented by Vicky Cakes all month long. We all get to use our talents in different ways; I‚Äôve used my gifts to train entrepreneurs to use webinars to build their businesses.
